9 May 1945. The Final German Instrument of Surrender was signed by the Allies and representatives of the German armed forces at the Soviet military headquarters in Berlin-Karlshorst. 
It officially ended the Second World War in Europe. Russians celebrate it as Victory Day. https://t.co/a8B9sLIUaA

9 May 1945. The Final German Instrument of Surrender was signed by the Allies and representatives of the German armed forces at the Soviet military headquarters in Berlin-Karlshorst. It officially ended the Second World War in Europe. Russians celebrate it as Victory Day https://t.co/JsfbjPPd5T

Instrument of unconditional surrender signed at Reims on 7th,May,1945.The legal document ended World War II.Signed in Karlshorst, Berlin, by representative (OKW)with the Supreme High Command of the Soviet Red Army,French and US representative signing as witness.Source wikipedia. https://t.co/4c6XT4uDab

Blast from the past May 8/9 1945 (thread): Unconditional surrender of the 3rd Reich becomes effective. It was first signed in the Allied HQ in Reims and ratified at the Red Army HQ in Berlin-Karlshorst. Official end of #WWII in Europe. But some German units surrendered later: https://t.co/bv3ZRaqOSc

Good morning all & on this day in 1945, the remaining Nazi high command surrendered to the Soviets and the Allies at Karlshorst in Berlin. With Hitler dead, and his successor Admiral Donitz in Flensburg,  Field Marshal Keitel signed for what remained of the Nazi state. https://t.co/1f9m6L1xme

Chief Air Marshall Sir Arthur Tedder and LtGen Carl Spaatz in the office of Marshall Georgy Zhukov before the German surrender was signed at Zhukov’s Headquarters at Karlshorst, Berlin, Germany, 7 May 1945 https://t.co/SnNmL73Uve

The act of military surrender was first signed at 02:41 on 7 May in SHAEF HQ at Reims, and a slightly modified document, considered the definitive German Instrument of Surrender, was signed on 8 May 1945 in Karlshorst, Berlin at 21:20 local time.

And Linke are safe. Gesine Lötzsch wins in Berlin-Lichtenberg, giving The Left the three seats they need to make it into the Bundestag with less than 5%.
Admittedly I had confused Berlin-Lichtenberg and and Marzahn – Hellersdorf constituencies. So I thought Pau losing was a bigger deal for a hot second. Thanks to @marius_saeltzer for reminding me.

Gregor Gysi wins Berlin-Treptow – Köpenick as expected. Will now come down to Berlin-Pankow and Berlin-Lichtenberg. The Linke won those by 9.2 and 15.1 points in 2017. So I still expect them to be safe.

Die Linke is winning only 2 out of the 4 Berlin single-member constituencies they hold: Lichtenberg and Treptow-Kopenick. They're behind in Pankow and Marzahn-Hellersdorf. They *need* to win Leipzig II as well to secure compensatory seats if they fall below 5% overall. #btw21 https://t.co/ICHkCwwxAa
